The paper deals with a game-theoretic model for decision-making in the presence of asymmetric information, which is a topic that falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). Additionally, the application of the model is in the field of cyber security, which suggests that the paper could also belong to the sub-category of cryptography and security (cs.CR). The model involves a learning agent and an observing agent, which implies that the paper could also be classified under the sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also deals with the updating of beliefs and the characterization of equilibria, which are topics that fall under the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG) and information theory (cs.IT).
